[1] UK (Wales)
Date: Mon 1 Aug 2016
Source: South Wales Evening Post [edited]
http://www.southwales-eveningpost.co.uk/mmr-vaccination/story-29572346-detail/story.html


Measles outbreak sees new MMR warning to parents in Swansea and Neath Port Talbot
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Children and adults who have not had the MMR 2 vaccine are being urged to do so

The NHS [National Health Service] in Wales has issued a stark warning over the importance of the MMR vaccine following a 4th case of measles in the space of a month.

In the last month there have been 4 cases across Swansea, Neath Port Talbot and Powys, one of which was hospitalised.

Public Health Wales says measles is a serious and highly contagious viral disease that can cause complications and can even prove fatal.

Dr Christopher Johnson, Acting Consultant in Health Protection for Public Health Wales, said 2 doses of the safe and effective MMR vaccine offer protection and anyone who hasn't had the vaccine is urged to get it free from their GP [general practitioner].

Dr Johnson added: "People may not think measles is serious but it is extremely easily spread and can even prove fatal.

"There is a vaccination programme for babies and toddlers but older children and adults can receive the vaccination at any time from their GP.

"If you are not sure if you have had your MMR, speak to your GP and ensure you protect yourself, your family and vulnerable members of the community such as babies who are too young to have the vaccine.

"Children should receive their 1st dose of the vaccine at 12 months of age and the 2nd at around 3 years and 4 months of age. However, we know in some areas vaccinations rates are dropping and I would urge any parent to prioritise the vaccination for their baby and any other members of the family who may not be protected."

Most measles sufferers develop a fever, cough, red eyes, a blocked nose and a blotchy rash.

It is also important if you think you may have measles to phone your GP or local hospital before attending. Those with symptoms are asked not to socialise with children, or other vulnerable individuals including infants, pregnant women, and those with a weakened immune system for around 10 days after symptoms start.

More information about measles is available from the Public Health Wales website: http://www.wales.nhs.uk/sites3/page.cfm?orgId=457&pid=25444 [including a figure and table of incidence of measles from 1996-2012 by year of occurrence and age of patient - Mod.LK].

[Byline: Steffan Thomas]

