[3] Taiwan (Taipei Songshan Airport)
Date: Wed 3 Aug 2016
Source: Focus Taiwan [edited]
http://focustaiwan.tw/news/asoc/201608030024.aspx


2 measles cases confirmed as originating from a domestic departure area at Taipei Songshan Airport
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Two cases of measles infection have been confirmed to have originated from a domestic departure area at Taipei Songshan Airport, and the Centers for Disease Control (CDC) urged the public Wed [3 Aug 2016] to be on alert if they have traveled to places where either of the 2 patients have visited between 26 Jul and 1 Aug [2016].

A 42-year-old man and a 25-year-old woman were confirmed to have contracted measles 1 Aug [2016], and their specimen tests suggest that the cases are a cluster infection, the CDC said.

The man departed for Kinmen 15 Jul [2016], returning to Taipei the following day, but developed fever, coughing and measles from 24-31 Jul [2016], when he sought medical attention. The woman, an airline ground staffer, worked at the same place where the man was infected 15 Jul [2016] and sought medication 30-31 Jul [2016] for the same symptoms.

Yen Che-chieh director of the CDC's northern district control center, said that as both patients had been in the same area of the airport between 1 p.m. and 1:20 p.m. 15 Jul [2016], they might have been infected by another source as yet unidentified.

Follow-up investigations show that 328 people have since been in contact with the 2 measles patients, with one of the women's co-workers having been infected 31 Jul [2016] and is now recovering at home.

Sixteen of the 328 people remained free of symptoms while 311 others are being watched for any signs of infection. The tracking will continue until 12 Aug [2016].

The 42-year-old drives to work and has not traveled much since then, but the 25-year-old takes public transport to and from work. The CDC advised people taking the MRT between the Nangang Exhibition Halls and Songshan Airport, and those who have taken the No. 620 and No. 270 buses to monitor their health.

They are advised to impose an 18-day health management program on themselves and, if they suspect they have been infected, should wear a surgical mask and see a doctor.

Measles is a highly contagious viral disease that can spread through the air, or through contact with an infected person's saliva or nose and throat discharge.

[Byline: Chen Wei-ting and S.C. Chang]

